# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: open-ran
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:open-ran/5g] Like earlier cellular systems, 5G networks divide service areas into smaller zones called cells, which are served by fixed cell sites.
[src:open-ran/5g] Compatible devices connect by radio to local base stations, which are linked to an operator's core network and to external networks such as the Internet through backhaul connections.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G can be deployed using low-band, mid-band, and high-band radio spectrum, with coverage and performance depending heavily on the frequencies used, network design, congestion, and device capabilities.
[src:open-ran/5g] Compared with 4G, 5G is designed to provide higher data rates, greater network capacity, lower latency, improved support for dense device deployments, and more flexible network management.
[src:open-ran/5g] Actual user speeds are typically much lower than peak values and vary by operator, location, spectrum band, signal quality, and network load.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G is used for mobile broadband, fixed wireless access, private and industrial networks, and machine-type communications.
[src:open-ran/5g] Its standards support features such as network slicing, edge computing, non-public networks, and ultra-reliable low-latency services, although these capabilities are not present in every deployment.
[src:open-ran/5g] The rollout of 5G has required new spectrum allocations and upgrades to radio access, transport, and core-network infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/5g] It has also raised issues involving deployment cost, energy use, vendor security, and public claims about radio-frequency health effects.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G is being deployed alongside 4G networks and is expected to coexist with them for many years.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2008, NASA and the Machine-to-Machine Intelligence Corporation (M2Mi) conducted nanosatellite communication studies that influenced early next-generation network concepts.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2012, New York University established NYU Wireless, a research center focused on millimeter-wave communication.
[src:open-ran/5g] The same year, the University of Surrey founded the 5G Innovation Centre, funded by £35 million from public and industry partners including Huawei and Samsung.
[src:open-ran/5g] Also in 2012, the European Union launched the *Mobile and Wireless Communications Enablers for the Twenty-Twenty Information Society (METIS)* project to align emerging network research with international standardization.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2013, the ITU-R Working Party 5D began studies on *IMT-2020*, later formalized as the 5G standard.
[src:open-ran/5g] During the same period, major firms such as Samsung Electronics, NTT Docomo, and Huawei conducted early trials.
[src:open-ran/5g] Samsung tested a prototype achieving more than 1 Gbit/s across 2 km using 8 × 8 MIMO antennas.
[src:open-ran/5g] NTT Docomo received a government award at CEATEC for high-speed network development, while Huawei announced a US$600 million program to advance mobile network technology.
[src:open-ran/5g] On April 3, 2019, South Korea launched its national network, the first full commercial deployment.
[src:open-ran/5g] Hours later, Verizon began limited service in select U.S. cities.
[src:open-ran/5g] In June 2019, Globe Telecom introduced the Philippines' first next-generation network, and in December 2019, AT&T launched a consumer service in the United States that expanded nationwide during 2020.
[src:open-ran/5g] Commercial 5G deployment expanded rapidly through 2020.
[src:open-ran/5g] Beyond public mobile networks, it was also adopted in private industrial and enterprise systems, including operation in unlicensed spectrum (NR-U) and licensed non-public networks (NPNs).
[src:open-ran/5g] Private 5G networks became important for Industry 4.0 automation and smart manufacturing.
[src:open-ran/5g] Early rollouts used non-standalone (NSA) mode—with 4G cores—before networks transitioned to standalone (SA) mode with dedicated 5G cores.
[src:open-ran/5g] South Korea’s 2019 rollout used equipment from Samsung, Ericsson, and Nokia; LG U Plus also deployed Huawei hardware.
[src:open-ran/5g] Samsung supplied most of the roughly 86,000 sites, while SK Telecom, KT Corporation, and LG U Plus concentrated coverage in major cities using the 3.5 GHz band under NSA operation.
[src:open-ran/5g] Reported download speeds averaged 200–400 Mbit/s, and subscriptions grew from about 260,000 to 4.7 million during 2019.
[src:open-ran/5g] Following these early deployments, T-Mobile US launched the first nationwide standalone network in 2020.
[src:open-ran/5g] Ericsson projected that by the mid-2020s, 5G networks would reach about 65 percent of the global population.
[src:open-ran/5g] Major suppliers of 5G radio and core systems included Altiostar, Cisco Systems, Datang Telecom/Fiberhome, Ericsson, Huawei, Nokia, Qualcomm, Samsung, and ZTE.
[src:open-ran/5g] Huawei was estimated to hold about 70 percent of global 5G base stations by 2023.
[src:open-ran/5g] By 2022, network speeds in many regions had stabilized, and operators began testing 5.5G upgrades to improve capacity and latency.
[src:open-ran/5g] By the early 2020s, large-scale commercial 5G networks were active across most developed markets, and rollout in developing regions was still accelerating.
[src:open-ran/5g] Small cells are low-power radio nodes that extend network capacity in dense or indoor areas.
[src:open-ran/5g] They operate over short distances, typically a few dozen to a few hundred metres, and are used to maintain coverage for mmWave signals.
[src:open-ran/5g] Massive multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems use large antenna arrays to increase capacity and spectral efficiency.
[src:open-ran/5g] They extend conventional MIMO by serving multiple users simultaneously and steering signals toward them to reduce interference.
[src:open-ran/5g] Beamforming directs radio energy toward specific users.
[src:open-ran/5g] In analogue beamforming, antenna outputs are combined to focus signal power in one direction.
[src:open-ran/5g] Digital beamforming transmits data streams across multiple layers to improve signal strength and reliability.
[src:open-ran/5g] Non-orthogonal multiple access assigns different power levels to users sharing the same frequency resources to improve spectral efficiency.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G NR uses polar codes for control channels and low-density parity-check codes (LDPC) for data channels, replacing the turbo codes used in 4G.
[src:open-ran/5g] Research has explored the use of 5G mmWave networks for wireless power transfer.
[src:open-ran/5g] Studies using wavelengths between 1 mm and 10 mm remain experimental.
[src:open-ran/5g] The 5G core (5GC) is a service-oriented, software-defined system that separates control and user planes and supports flexible deployment.
[src:open-ran/5g] It replaces the 4G Evolved Packet Core with modular, software-based network functions.
[src:open-ran/5g] Software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) enable software-based configuration, scaling, and management of networks.
[src:open-ran/5g] Together with network slicing, these technologies support applications such as the Internet of things, connected vehicles, and industrial automation.
[src:open-ran/5g] Service-based architecture (SBA) integrates SDN and NFV principles and replaces the 4G EPC framework with modular network functions that communicate through RESTful APIs.
[src:open-ran/5g] Each function registers with a network repository function (NRF), which enables independent scaling and interoperability.
[src:open-ran/5g] Each network function performs a defined role within the 5G core, replacing or extending elements from the 4G EPC.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G networks use multiple parts of the radio spectrum.
[src:open-ran/5g] They operate across three main frequency ranges—low, mid, and high bands—which balance speed, coverage, and signal quality differently.
[src:open-ran/5g] Between 2016 and 2019, regulators in many regions, including the United States and the European Union, reallocated large sections of spectrum for 5G through auctions and new licensing rules.
[src:open-ran/5g] By 2019, more than 50 countries had assigned or planned to assign 5G frequencies.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 3GPP Release 16, the standard added 5G NR-U, allowing operation in both unlicensed and licensed spectrum.
[src:open-ran/5g] Low- and mid-band 5G provide broad coverage and reliable indoor reception.
[src:open-ran/5g] High-band signals weaken rapidly and may lose over 100 dB when passing through common building materials.
[src:open-ran/5g] Operators use beamforming antennas, small cells, and signal repeaters to extend range and improve indoor coverage.
[src:open-ran/5g] Technologies such as License Assisted Access (LAA) and LTE-WLAN Aggregation (LWA) let mobile networks share unlicensed spectrum with Wi-Fi.
[src:open-ran/5g] Cloud-based RAN systems and dense small-cell layouts help narrow the performance gap between cellular and Wi-Fi links.
[src:open-ran/5g] The ITU-R defines three main application areas for 5G: enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), and massive machine-type communications (mMTC).
[src:open-ran/5g] These categories describe the main uses of 5G: faster mobile connections (eMBB), highly reliable and responsive communication (URLLC), and large-scale links between machines (mMTC).
[src:open-ran/5g] By 2020, eMBB was widely deployed, while URLLC and mMTC were still in development.
[src:open-ran/5g] Enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) provides much faster internet and higher capacity than 4G.
[src:open-ran/5g] It supports intensive data use in busy areas such as city centres, stadiums, and transport hubs.
[src:open-ran/5g] Ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) are designed for time-critical applications such as factory automation, remote medical procedures, and traffic systems.
[src:open-ran/5g] Shorter transmission delays improve precision and reliability.
[src:open-ran/5g] Massive machine-type communications (mMTC) connect large numbers of low-power devices such as sensors and meters.
[src:open-ran/5g] These networks underpin the Internet of things (IoT) by allowing machines to exchange data autonomously in industry, transport, and urban systems.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G is used in transport, manufacturing, and energy systems that require constant, low-latency communication.
[src:open-ran/5g] The 5G Automotive Association develops vehicle-to-everything (C-V2X) standards that allow cars to exchange safety information with nearby vehicles and infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/5g] Drones and autonomous vehicles use 5G for navigation, remote control, and real-time data transmission.
[src:open-ran/5g] Low-latency connections also enable digital twin models—virtual copies of machines or buildings that show real-time performance data used for monitoring and maintenance.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G extends to public safety, broadband access, and media delivery.
[src:open-ran/5g] Emergency services use it for live video, data, and reliable push-to-talk communication.
[src:open-ran/5g] Fixed wireless access (FWA) provides home and business broadband using 5G radio links instead of wired connections, especially in rural areas where laying cables is costly.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G Broadcast trials in Europe show that local 5G networks can deliver live television and radio to many devices simultaneously without using mobile data plans.
[src:open-ran/5g] Voice over NR (VoNR) allows phone calls to be made over 5G's internet-based network, similar to Voice over LTE (VoLTE) on 4G.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G can deliver much higher data rates than 4G, up to ten times faster.
[src:open-ran/5g] Theoretical peak download speeds reach up to 20 Gbit/s.
[src:open-ran/5g] In practice, average 5G download speeds in the United States have been measured at about 186 Mbit/s by T-Mobile, while South Korea in 2022 led globally with averages near 430 Mbit/s.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G networks are also designed to provide much greater total capacity and efficiency than 4G, with up to a hundredfold projected increase.
[src:open-ran/5g] The most widely deployed version, sub-6 GHz (mid-band) 5G, provides speeds of roughly 10–1000 Mbit/s with wider reach than mmWave bands.
[src:open-ran/5g] C-Band (n77/n78) was introduced in the U.S. in 2022, though activation by Verizon and AT&T was briefly delayed due to FAA safety concerns.
[src:open-ran/5g] The highest 5G speed measured in a deployed network is 5.9 Gbit/s (2023).
[src:open-ran/5g] Low-band frequencies such as n5 cover larger areas per cell but deliver lower data rates of around 5–250 Mbit/s.
[src:open-ran/5g] Typical *air latency* for 5G is around 8–12 ms, excluding retransmissions and handovers.
[src:open-ran/5g] Verizon reported about 30 ms latency in early deployments.
[src:open-ran/5g] Edge servers located near base stations can reduce round-trip time to roughly 14 ms and minimize jitter to about 1.8 ms.
[src:open-ran/5g] Latency increases substantially during handovers, ranging from 50 to 150 ms depending on network conditions.
[src:open-ran/5g] Ongoing research focuses on reducing these interruptions by adjusting handover margins and time-to-trigger parameters.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G uses adaptive modulation and coding schemes (MCS) to maintain a low block error rate (BLER).
[src:open-ran/5g] When the error rate exceeds a threshold, the system automatically switches to a lower MCS to prioritize reliability over speed.
[src:open-ran/5g] The range of 5G varies with transmit power, frequency, and interference.
[src:open-ran/5g] High-frequency mmWave bands (e.g., n258) have a shorter range than mid-band (n78), which in turn has a shorter range than low-band (n5).
[src:open-ran/5g] Operators use network simulation and drive testing to measure the actual range and coverage of these bands, as real-world performance can differ from marketing claims.
[src:open-ran/5g] The term 5G was first associated with the International Telecommunication Union's IMT-2020 standard.
[src:open-ran/5g] It defines peak download and upload rates of 20 and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:open-ran/5g] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) later proposed its 5G New Radio (NR) technology for IMT-2020.
[src:open-ran/5g] Early FR1 deployments reusing 4G infrastructure (non-standalone mode) have been reported to provide 15–50 percent higher throughput than advanced 4G networks under favorable conditions.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G networks can operate in Non-Standalone (NSA) mode using existing LTE infrastructure or Standalone (SA) mode using a dedicated 5G Core (5GC) network.
[src:open-ran/5g] Other organizations also contribute to 5G standards.
[src:open-ran/5g] The DECT-2020 specification defines DECT NR+, a non-cellular, mesh-based radio system recognized by ITU as part of 5G.
[src:open-ran/5g] The IEEE defines standards for wired links between the remote radio unit (RRU) and the baseband unit (BBU).
[src:open-ran/5g] 5Gi was developed in India by IIT Madras, IIT Hyderabad, the Telecommunications Standards Development Society India (TSDSI) and the Centre of Excellence in Wireless Technology (CEWiT).
[src:open-ran/5g] It extends 5G coverage in rural and remote areas through low-mobility large-cell (LMLC) configurations.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5Gi was merged in April 2022 into the global 5G NR standard in 3GPP Release 17.
[src:open-ran/5g] In the Internet of things (IoT), 3GPP defines the evolution of NB-IoT and eMTC to support low-power wide-area applications such as connected sensors and meters.
[src:open-ran/5g] 3GPP standards also define advanced communication services for voice and connected devices.
[src:open-ran/5g] 3GPP defines Voice over NR as a technology that enables native, high-quality voice over a 5G Standalone network through the 5G System Architecture.
[src:open-ran/5g] Unlike early 5G Non-Standalone deployments that relied on Evolved Packet System Fallback, VoNR integrates directly with the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) used in VoLTE.
[src:open-ran/5g] It uses NAS protocols to establish high-priority QoS flows that support URLLC requirements for voice traffic.
[src:open-ran/5g] Support for 5G Standalone is a prerequisite for VoNR.
[src:open-ran/5g] VoNR benefits from the enhanced security architecture of the 5G Core network, including improved subscriber identity protection.
[src:open-ran/5g] VoNR delivers superior audio quality through the Enhanced Voice Services (EVS) codec, which must adhere to rigorous terminal acoustic requirements and standardized testing procedures.
[src:open-ran/5g] Most phones released since 2023 (such as the iPhone 15 series and newer flagship devices) support VoNR, but availability depends on carrier enablement in specific areas.
[src:open-ran/5g] 3GPP also defines non-terrestrial networks (NTN) that use satellites and airborne platforms to provide coverage where ground networks are impractical.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G-Advanced, also known as 5.5G or 5G-A, is defined in 3GPP Release 18 as a transition between 5G and 6G.
[src:open-ran/5g] It adds features for more efficient spectrum use, lower energy demand, and higher reliability.
[src:open-ran/5g] The release introduces AI- and ML-based network management, extended-reality services, and communication support for autonomous systems.
[src:open-ran/5g] Release 18 specifies improved time-synchronization methods independent of the GNSS and built-in geolocation functions.
[src:open-ran/5g] It extends non-terrestrial support to satellite and airborne communication.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G Reduced Capability (RedCap) in 3GPP Release 17 is designed to bridge the gap between high-performance 5G devices and low-power IoT technologies such as LTE-M and NB-IoT.
[src:open-ran/5g] It was created to address use cases between Enhanced Mobile Broadband (eMBB), Ultra-Reliable Low-Latency Communications (URLLC), and Massive Machine-Type Communication (mMTC) technologies.
[src:open-ran/5g] The Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) compiled the first database of 5G-compatible products, listing 23 manufacturers and 33 models across categories such as smartphones, hotspots, and customer-premises equipment.
[src:open-ran/5g] Later surveys recorded more than one hundred announced products from over fifty vendors.
[src:open-ran/5g] Early 5G modem chipsets were released by Intel, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Samsung, followed by additional platforms in subsequent product generations.
[src:open-ran/5g] The Samsung Galaxy S10 5G was among the first smartphones to support 5G networks.
[src:open-ran/5g] Other early 5G models included the Nokia 8.3 5G, designed for operation across low- to mid-band frequencies; the Google Pixel 5 and Pixel 4a (5G); and Apple's iPhone 12 series, the company's first generation with 5G capability.
[src:open-ran/5g] By the early 2020s, most high-end smartphones featured 5G capability, while some consumer devices still lack full support.
[src:open-ran/5g] As a result, the practical benefits for mid range phone users have been modest, and 5G adoption has lagged behind expectations.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2019, the European Commission and the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) warned that 5G networks could expand potential attack surfaces for state actors, recommending diversification of suppliers.
[src:open-ran/5g] Nokia and Ericsson are the only European manufacturers.
[src:open-ran/5g] Researchers from ETH Zurich and partner universities found weaknesses in the 5G authentication process that could expose users to new security risks.
[src:open-ran/5g] They concluded that the system was still immature and that its higher data capacity could increase exposure to attacks.
[src:open-ran/5g] A 2022 study identified a design flaw in the Evolved Packet System (EPS) that could affect device behavior during network switching.
[src:open-ran/5g] Growth of the Internet of things increases the number of devices connected through 5G.
[src:open-ran/5g] IoT Analytics estimated growth from about 7 billion devices in 2018 to over 21 billion by 2025, raising exposure to DDoS attacks, cryptojacking, and other cyberattacks.
[src:open-ran/5g] Concerns about espionage and data access have influenced national policies.
[src:open-ran/5g] The United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom have restricted or banned Chinese-made equipment.
[src:open-ran/5g] A 2012 report by the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence concluded that equipment from Huawei and ZTE could pose national-security risks.
[src:open-ran/5g] Later assessments by U.S. intelligence agencies warned that Huawei products could allow covert data access.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2022, the FBI reported that Huawei equipment near U.S. military bases could interfere with nuclear communications.
[src:open-ran/5g] Huawei and the Chinese government deny the allegations.
[src:open-ran/5g] Analysts note that China's National Security Law could require companies to provide data to authorities if requested.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2020, the United States Department of State launched The Clean Network initiative to promote data privacy and security among allied nations.
[src:open-ran/5g] By year-end, more than 60 countries and 200 telecommunications companies had joined, including most NATO, EU, and OECD members.
[src:open-ran/5g] Some 5G bands, such as n258 at 26 GHz, are close to frequencies used for passive remote sensing by weather and Earth observation satellites, including water vapor measurements at 23.8 GHz.
[src:open-ran/5g] Interference with satellite observations could reduce the accuracy of numerical weather prediction models and affect sectors such as commercial aviation.
[src:open-ran/5g] Navy warned that out-of-band emissions from 5G transmissions near 24 GHz could degrade forecasts by up to 30 %.
[src:open-ran/5g] The 2019 World Radiocommunication Conference set an interim limit of −33 dBW until 2027, followed by −39 dBW.
[src:open-ran/5g] The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) warned that these limits could reduce forecast reliability.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2021–2022, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned that some 5G signals could interfere with aircraft radar altimeters, which operate at 4.2–4.4 GHz, while new 5G services use 3.7–4.0 GHz.
[src:open-ran/5g] Europe uses lower frequencies (3.4–3.8 GHz), reducing the risk.
[src:open-ran/5g] Some 5G allocations overlap with frequencies used by C band satellite communication systems.
[src:open-ran/5g] Interference can occur when networks operate in 3.3–3.6 GHz, near satellite reception at 3.4–4.2 GHz Mitigation uses low-noise block downconverters and waveguide filters.
[src:open-ran/5g] 5G and Wi-Fi 6E share the 6 GHz band, which enables efficient spectrum use but requires coordination to prevent interference.
[src:open-ran/5g] Both operate under unlicensed conditions in the US and EU, supporting NR-U and Wi-Fi 6E technologies.
[src:open-ran/5g] Analysts note that marketing of 5G has often overstated its capabilities.
[src:open-ran/5g] Common concerns include limited user benefits, short range of mmWave signals, and rebranding of non-5G improvements as 5G.
[src:open-ran/5g] A 2020 survey by McKinsey & Company found that operators identified few immediately profitable use cases.
[src:open-ran/5g] Consumer surveys show mixed attitudes, with skepticism about marketing claims and uneven coverage in early deployments.
[src:open-ran/5g] Industry groups and network operators state that 5G enables faster speeds and lower latency, though results depend on infrastructure rollout and available spectrum.
[src:open-ran/5g] In contrast to the initial excitement about the prospects, many firms striving for deployment have encountered reality, users are not eager to upgrade the technology.
[src:open-ran/5g] Five years after its launch, a majority of users have yet to transition to the new standard.
[src:open-ran/5g] Public concern about the effects of wireless signals predates 5G technology.
[src:open-ran/5g] Similar concerns were raised about earlier mobile standards in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:open-ran/5g] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "exposure to intense, direct amounts of non-ionizing radiation may result in tissue damage due to heat.
[src:open-ran/5g] Some critics argue that existing exposure limits are too lenient or influenced by industry lobbying.
[src:open-ran/5g] Claims that the use of 5G mobile networks can cause cancer are unsupported by scientific evidence.
[src:open-ran/5g] Several books making unverified claims about wireless health effects have been published.
[src:open-ran/5g] One, by Joseph Mercola, alleged links to ADHD, heart disease, and brain cancer.
[src:open-ran/5g] Mercola was criticized for promoting misinformation during the COVID-19 pandemic and warned by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for selling unapproved COVID-19 cures.
[src:open-ran/5g] According to *The New York Times*, controversy regarding 5G health effects partly originated from an unpublished 2000 report by physicist Bill P.
[src:open-ran/5g] Curry for the Broward County School Board, which incorrectly concluded that higher-frequency microwaves are absorbed more deeply by the brain.
[src:open-ran/5g] Later analyses showed that this was a misunderstanding of *in vitro* research results.
[src:open-ran/5g] Experts noted that millimeter-wave frequencies used by 5G cannot penetrate the skin or reach internal organs.
[src:open-ran/5g] In a 2019 article, the same newspaper reported that RT America promoted claims linking 5G to diseases such as brain cancer, infertility, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:open-ran/5g] The network aired several such programs in 2019, later cited by numerous blogs and websites.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2019, cities such as Brussels and Geneva temporarily halted 5G rollouts pending radiation assessments.
[src:open-ran/5g] The Swiss Telecommunications Association stated that studies had not demonstrated adverse health effects from 5G exposure.
[src:open-ran/5g] Similar debates occurred in the Netherlands, the United States, and the United Kingdom, where some municipalities briefly delayed deployments or issued precautionary statements.
[src:open-ran/5g] The Food and Drug Administration maintains that existing exposure limits for cellphone radiofrequency energy are sufficient to protect public health.
[src:open-ran/5g] Low-level electromagnetic fields (EMF) can have measurable biological effects in plants and animals, but research remains inconclusive about health risks to humans.
[src:open-ran/5g] A 2019 meta-analysis found that while many *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies detected biological responses to radiofrequency exposure, the evidence did not establish health risks.
[src:open-ran/5g] The rollout of 5G technology began during the COVID-19 pandemic, prompting conspiracy theories that linked 5G to the pandemic.
[src:open-ran/5g] These claims led to arson attacks on telecom masts in parts of Europe, including the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and Italy.
[src:open-ran/5g] In the United Kingdom, at least 61 mobile masts were reportedly set on fire.
[src:open-ran/5g] During the early months of the pandemic, Australian anti-lockdown protesters carried anti-5G signs, later connected to broader conspiracy groups.
[src:open-ran/5g] The second claims that 5G causes COVID-19.
[src:open-ran/5g] Some versions claim the pandemic hid illnesses blamed on 5G, while others suggest COVID-19 began in Wuhan, one of the first cities with early 5G rollout.
[src:open-ran/5g] The marketing of pre-5G technologies refers to the promotion of enhanced 4G networks as precursors or alternatives to 5G.
[src:open-ran/5g] Before and during early 5G deployment, some mobile network operators used terms such as "pre-5G", "5G-ready", "4.5G", and "5G Evolution" for upgraded LTE Advanced or LTE Advanced Pro networks.
[src:open-ran/5g] These networks could use features such as carrier aggregation, 256-QAM, and 4×4 MIMO to increase data rates, but they did not use 5G NR, the radio access technology standardized for 5G networks.
[src:open-ran/5g] A notable example was 5G Evolution, introduced by AT&T in 2017 to market higher-speed LTE service.
[src:open-ran/5g] AT&T described the service as "a foundation for our evolution to 5G while the 5G standards are being finalized", but technology publications criticized the branding as misleading because the underlying network remained based on LTE technologies rather than 5G.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2019, Sprint sued AT&T, alleging that the 5G Evolution and "5GE" branding misled consumers into believing that they were receiving 5G service.
[src:open-ran/5g] In 2020, the National Advertising Review Board recommended that AT&T stop using "5G Evolution" and related claims in advertising, finding that the terms were misleading; AT&T said it disagreed with the decision but would comply with the self-regulatory process.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A **cellular network** or **mobile network** is a telecommunications network where the link to and from end nodes is wireless and the network is distributed over land areas called ***cells***, each served by at least one fixed-location transceiver (such as a base station).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] These base stations provide the cell with the network coverage which can be used for transmission of voice, data, and other types of content via radio waves.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Each cell's coverage area is determined by factors such as the power of the transceiver, the terrain, and the frequency band being used.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A cell typically uses a different set of frequencies from neighboring cells, to avoid interference and provide guaranteed service quality within each cell.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] When joined, these cells provide radio coverage over a wide geographic area.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The design of cellular networks allows for seamless handover, enabling uninterrupted communication when a device moves from one cell to another.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Modern cellular networks utilize advanced technologies such as Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO), beamforming, and small cells to enhance network capacity and efficiency.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Major telecommunications providers have deployed voice and data cellular networks over most of the inhabited land area of Earth.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This allows mobile phones and other devices to be connected to the public switched telephone network and public Internet access.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In addition to traditional voice and data services, cellular networks now support internet of things (IoT) applications, connecting devices such as smart meters, vehicles, and industrial sensors.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The evolution of cellular networks from 1G to 5G has progressively introduced faster speeds, lower latency, and support for a larger number of devices, enabling advanced applications in fields such as healthcare, transportation, and smart cities.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In a cellular radio system, a land area to be supplied with radio service is divided into cells in a pattern dependent on terrain and reception characteristics.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] These cell patterns roughly take the form of regular shapes, such as hexagons, squares, or circles although hexagonal cells are conventional.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Each of these cells is assigned with multiple frequencies (*f*1 – *f*6) which have corresponding radio base stations.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The group of frequencies can be reused in other cells, provided that the same frequencies are not reused in adjacent cells, which would cause co-channel interference.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This strategy is viable because a given radio frequency can be reused in a different area for an unrelated transmission.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In contrast, a single transmitter can only handle one transmission for a given frequency.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Inevitably, there is some level of interference from the signal from the other cells which use the same frequency.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Consequently, there must be at least one cell gap between cells which reuse the same frequency in a standard frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) system.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Consider the case of a taxi company, where each radio has a manually operated channel selector knob to tune to different frequencies.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As drivers move around, they change from channel to channel.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The drivers are aware of which frequency approximately covers some area.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] When they do not receive a signal from the transmitter, they try other channels until finding one that works.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The taxi drivers only speak one at a time when invited by the base station operator.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This is a form of time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The idea to establish a standard cellular phone network was first proposed on December 11, 1947.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This proposal was put forward by Douglas H.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Ring, a Bell Labs engineer, in an internal memo suggesting the development of a cellular telephone system by AT&T.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The first commercial cellular network, the 1G generation, was launched in Japan by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1979, initially in the metropolitan area of Tokyo.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] However, NTT did not initially commercialize the system; the early launch was motivated by an effort to understand a practical cellular system rather than by an interest to profit from it.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In 1981, the Nordic Mobile Telephone system was created as the first network to cover an entire country.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The network was released in 1981 in Sweden and Norway, then in Finland and Denmark in early 1982.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Televerket, a state-owned corporation responsible for telecommunications in Sweden, launched the system.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In September 1981, Jan Stenbeck, a financier and businessman, launched Comvik, a Swedish telecommunications company.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Comvik was the first European telecommunications firm to challenge the state's telephone monopoly on the industry.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] According to sources, Comvik was the first to launch a commercial automatic cellular system before Televerket launched its own in October 1981.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] However, at the time of the new network's release, the Swedish Post and Telecom Authority threatened to shut down the system after claiming that the company had used an unlicensed automatic gear that could interfere with its own networks.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In December 1981, Sweden awarded Comvik with a license to operate its own automatic cellular network in the spirit of market competition.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] First-generation cellular network technology continued to expand its reach to the rest of the world.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In 1990, Millicom Inc., a telecommunications service provider, strategically partnered with Comvik's international cellular operations to become Millicom International Cellular SA.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The company went on to establish a 1G systems foothold in Ghana, Africa under the brand name Mobitel.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In 2006, the company's Ghana operations were renamed to Tigo.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The wireless revolution began in the early 1990s, leading to the transition from analog to digital networks.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, was adapted for cellular networks by the early 1990s, with the wide adoption of power MOSFET, LDMOS (RF amplifier), and RF CMOS (RF circuit) devices leading to the development and proliferation of digital wireless mobile networks.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The first commercial digital cellular network, the 2G generation, was launched in 1991.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This sparked competition in the sector as the new operators challenged the incumbent 1G analog network operators.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] With FDMA, the transmitting and receiving frequencies used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Each cellular call was assigned a pair of frequencies (one for base to mobile, the other for mobile to base) to provide full-duplex operation.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The original AMPS systems had 666 channel pairs, 333 each for the CLEC "A" system and ILEC "B" system.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The number of channels was expanded to 416 pairs per carrier, but ultimately the number of RF channels limits the number of calls that a cell site could handle.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] FDMA is a familiar technology to telephone companies, which used frequency-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before time-division multiplexing rendered FDM obsolete.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] With TDMA, the transmitting and receiving time slots used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] TDMA typically uses digital signaling to store and forward bursts of voice data that are fit into time slices for transmission, and expanded at the receiving end to produce a somewhat normal-sounding voice at the receiver.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] TDMA must introduce latency (time delay) into the audio signal.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As long as the latency time is short enough that the delayed audio is not heard as an echo, it is not problematic.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] TDMA is a familiar technology for telephone companies, which used time-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before packet switching rendered TDM obsolete.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The principle of CDMA is based on spread spectrum technology developed for military use during World War II and improved during the Cold War into direct-sequence spread spectrum that was used for early CDMA cellular systems and Wi-Fi.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] DSSS allows multiple simultaneous phone conversations to take place on a single wideband RF channel, without needing to channelize them in time or frequency.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Although more sophisticated than older multiple access schemes (and unfamiliar to legacy telephone companies because it was not developed by Bell Labs), CDMA has scaled well to become the basis for 3G cellular radio systems.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Other available methods of multiplexing such as MIMO, a more sophisticated version of antenna diversity, combined with active beamforming provides much greater spatial multiplexing ability compared to original AMPS cells, that typically only addressed one to three unique spaces.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Massive MIMO deployment allows much greater channel reuse, thus increasing the number of subscribers per cell site, greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Quadrature Amplitude Modulation (QAM) modems offer an increasing number of bits per symbol, allowing more users per megahertz of bandwidth (and decibels of SNR), greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The key characteristic of a cellular network is the ability to reuse frequencies to increase both coverage and capacity.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As described above, adjacent cells must use different frequencies, however, there is no problem with two cells sufficiently far apart operating on the same frequency, provided the masts and cellular network users' equipment do not transmit with too much power.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The elements that determine frequency reuse are the reuse distance and the reuse factor.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] where *R* is the cell radius and *N* is the number of cells per cluster.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Cells may vary in radius from 1 to 30 kilometres (0.62 to 18.64 mi).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The boundaries of the cells can also overlap between adjacent cells and large cells can be divided into smaller cells.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The frequency reuse factor is the rate at which the same frequency can be used in the network.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] It is *1/K* (or *K* according to some books) where *K* is the number of cells which cannot use the same frequencies for transmission.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Common values for the frequency reuse factor are 1/3, 1/4, 1/7, 1/9 and 1/12 (or 3, 4, 7, 9 and 12, depending on notation).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In case of *N* sector antennas on the same base station site, each with different direction, the base station site can serve N different sectors.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A **reuse pattern** of *N/K* denotes a further division in frequency among *N* sector antennas per site.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Some current and historical reuse patterns are 3/7 (North American AMPS), 6/4 (Motorola NAMPS), and 3/4 (GSM).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] If the total available bandwidth is *B*, each cell can only use a number of frequency channels corresponding to a bandwidth of *B/K*, and each sector can use a bandwidth of *B/NK*.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Code-division multiple access-based systems use a wider frequency band to achieve the same rate of transmission as FDMA, but this is compensated for by the ability to use a frequency reuse factor of 1, for example using a reuse pattern of 1/1.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In other words, adjacent base station sites use the same frequencies, and the different base stations and users are separated by codes rather than frequencies.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] While *N* is shown as 1 in this example, that does not mean the CDMA cell has only one sector, but rather that the entire cell bandwidth is also available to each sector individually.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Recently also orthogonal frequency-division multiple access based systems such as LTE are being deployed with a frequency reuse of 1.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Since such systems do not spread the signal across the frequency band, inter-cell radio resource management is important to coordinate resource allocation between different cell sites and to limit the inter-cell interference.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] There are various means of inter-cell interference coordination (ICIC) already defined in the standard.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Coordinated scheduling, multi-site MIMO or multi-site beamforming are other examples for inter-cell radio resource management that might be standardized in the future.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Cell towers frequently use a directional signal to improve reception in higher-traffic areas.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) limits omnidirectional cell tower signals to 100 watts of power.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] If the tower has directional antennas, the FCC allows the cell operator to emit up to 500 watts of effective radiated power (ERP).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Although the original cell towers created an even, omnidirectional signal, were at the centers of the cells and were omnidirectional, a cellular map can be redrawn with the cellular telephone towers located at the corners of the hexagons where three cells converge.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Each tower has three sets of directional antennas aimed in three different directions with 120 degrees for each cell (totaling 360 degrees) and receiving/transmitting into three different cells at different frequencies.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This provides a minimum of three channels, and three towers for each cell and greatly increases the chances of receiving a usable signal from at least one direction.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The numbers in the illustration are channel numbers, which repeat every 3 cells.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Large cells can be subdivided into smaller cells for high volume areas.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Cell phone companies also use this directional signal to improve reception along highways and inside buildings like stadiums and arenas.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Practically every cellular system has some kind of broadcast mechanism.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This can be used directly for distributing information to multiple mobiles.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Commonly, for example in mobile telephony systems, the most important use of broadcast information is to set up channels for one-to-one communication between the mobile transceiver and the base station.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The three different paging procedures generally adopted are sequential, parallel and selective paging.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Paging takes place by sending the broadcast message to all of those cells.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Paging messages can be used for information transfer.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This happens in pagers, in CDMA systems for sending SMS messages, and in the UMTS system where it allows for low downlink latency in packet-based connections.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In LTE/4G, the Paging procedure is initiated by the MME when data packets need to be delivered to the UE.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In a primitive taxi system, when the taxi moved away from a first tower and closer to a second tower, the taxi driver manually switched from one frequency to another as needed.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] If communication was interrupted due to a loss of a signal, the taxi driver asked the base station operator to repeat the message on a different frequency.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In a cellular system, as the distributed mobile transceivers move from cell to cell during an ongoing continuous communication, switching from one cell frequency to a different cell frequency is done electronically without interruption and without a base station operator or manual switching.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Typically, a new channel is automatically selected for the mobile unit on the new base station which will serve it.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The mobile unit then automatically switches from the current channel to the new channel and communication continues.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The exact details of the mobile system's move from one base station to the other vary considerably from system to system (see the example below for how a mobile phone network manages handover).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The most common example of a cellular network is a mobile phone (cell phone) network.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A mobile phone is a portable telephone which receives or makes calls through a cell site (base station) or transmitting tower.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Radio waves are used to transfer signals to and from the cell phone.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Modern mobile phone networks use cells because radio frequencies are a limited, shared resource.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Cell-sites and handsets change frequency under computer control and use low power transmitters so that the usually limited number of radio frequencies can be simultaneously used by many callers with less interference.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A cellular network is used by the mobile phone operator to achieve both coverage and capacity for their subscribers.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Large geographic areas are split into smaller cells to avoid line-of-sight signal loss and to support a large number of active phones in that area.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] All of the cell sites are connected to telephone exchanges (or switches), which in turn connect to the public telephone network.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In cities, each cell site may have a range of up to approximately 1⁄2 mile (0.80 km), while in rural areas, the range could be as much as 5 miles (8.0 km).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] It is possible that in clear open areas, a user may receive signals from a cell site 25 miles (40 km) away.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In rural areas with low-band coverage and tall towers, basic voice and messaging service may reach 50 miles (80 km), with limitations on bandwidth and number of simultaneous calls.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Since almost all mobile phones use cellular technology, including GSM, CDMA, and AMPS (analog), the term "cell phone" is in some regions, notably the US, used interchangeably with "mobile phone".
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] However, satellite phones are mobile phones that do not communicate directly with a ground-based cellular tower but may do so indirectly by way of a satellite.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The transition from existing analog to the digital standard followed a very different path in Europe and the US.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As a consequence, multiple digital standards surfaced in the US, while Europe and many countries converged towards the GSM standard.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This network is the foundation of the GSM system network.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] There are many functions that are performed by this network in order to make sure customers get the desired service including mobility management, registration, call set-up, and handover.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Any phone connects to the network via an RBS (Radio Base Station) at a corner of the corresponding cell which in turn connects to the Mobile switching center (MSC).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The MSC provides a connection to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The link from a phone to the RBS is called an *uplink* while the other way is termed *downlink*.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Radio channels effectively use the transmission medium through the use of the following multiplexing and access schemes: frequency-division multiple access (FDMA), time-division multiple access (TDMA), code-division multiple access (CDMA), and space-division multiple access (SDMA).
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As the phone user moves from one cell area to another cell while a call is in progress, the mobile station will search for a new channel to attach to in order not to drop the call.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Once a new channel is found, the network will command the mobile unit to switch to the new channel and at the same time switch the call onto the new channel.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] With CDMA, multiple CDMA handsets share a specific radio channel.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The signals are separated by using a pseudonoise code (PN code) that is specific to each phone.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As the user moves from one cell to another, the handset sets up radio links with multiple cell sites (or sectors of the same site) simultaneously.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This is known as "soft handoff" because, unlike with traditional cellular technology, there is no one defined point where the phone switches to the new cell.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In IS-95 inter-frequency handovers and older analog systems such as NMT it will typically be impossible to test the target channel directly while communicating.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In this case, other techniques have to be used such as pilot beacons in IS-95.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This means that there is almost always a brief break in the communication while searching for the new channel followed by the risk of an unexpected return to the old channel.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] If there is no ongoing communication or the communication can be interrupted, it is possible for the mobile unit to spontaneously move from one cell to another and then notify the base station with the strongest signal.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The effect of frequency on cell coverage means that different frequencies serve better for different uses.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Low frequencies, such as 450 MHz NMT, serve very well for countryside coverage.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] GSM 900 (900 MHz) is suitable for light urban coverage.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] GSM 1800 (1.8 GHz) starts to be limited by structural walls.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] UMTS, at 2.1 GHz is quite similar in coverage to GSM 1800.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Higher frequencies are a disadvantage when it comes to coverage, but it is a decided advantage when it comes to capacity.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Picocells, covering e.g. one floor of a building, become possible, and the same frequency can be used for cells which are practically neighbors.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] Cell service area may also vary due to interference from transmitting systems, both within and around that cell.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] This is true especially in CDMA based systems.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] The receiver requires a certain signal-to-noise ratio, and the transmitter should not send with too high transmission power in view to not cause interference with other transmitters.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As the receiver moves away from the transmitter, the power received decreases, so the power control algorithm of the transmitter increases the power it transmits to restore the level of received power.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] As the interference (noise) rises above the received power from the transmitter, and the power of the transmitter cannot be increased anymore, the signal becomes corrupted and eventually unusable.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In CDMA-based systems, the effect of interference from other mobile transmitters in the same cell on coverage area is very marked and has a special name, *cell breathing*.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] One can see examples of cell coverage by studying some of the coverage maps provided by real operators on their web sites or by looking at independently crowdsourced maps such as Opensignal or CellMapper.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] In certain cases they may mark the site of the transmitter; in others, it can be calculated by working out the point of strongest coverage.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] A cellular repeater is used to extend cell coverage into larger areas.
[src:open-ran/cellular-network] They range from wideband repeaters for consumer use in homes and offices to smart or digital repeaters for industrial needs.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] NFV relies upon traditional server-virtualization techniques, such as those used in enterprise IT.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] For example, a virtual session border controller could be deployed to protect a network without the typical cost and complexity of obtaining and installing physical network protection units.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Other examples of NFV include virtualized load balancers, firewalls, intrusion detection devices and WAN accelerators to name a few.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Decoupling the network function software from the customized hardware platform creates a flexible network architecture that enables agile network management, faster new service roll outs with significant reduction in CAPEX and OPEX.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Product development within the telecommunication industry has traditionally followed rigorous standards for stability, protocol adherence and quality, reflected by the use of the term carrier grade to designate equipment demonstrating this high reliability and performance factor.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] While this model worked well in the past, it inevitably led to long product cycles, a slow pace of development and reliance on proprietary or specific hardware, e.g., bespoke application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In October 2012, a group of telecom operators published a white paper at a conference in Darmstadt, Germany, on software-defined networking (SDN) and OpenFlow.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The Call for Action concluding the White Paper led to the creation of the Network Functions Virtualization (NFV) Industry Specification Group (ISG) within the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The ISG was made up of representatives from the telecommunication industry from Europe and beyond.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] ETSI ISG NFV addresses many aspects, including functional architecture, information model, data model, protocols, APIs, testing, reliability, security, future evolutions, etc.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The ETSI ISG NFV has announced the Release 5 of its specifications since May 2021 aiming to produce new specifications and extend the already published specifications based on new features and enhancements.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Since the publication of the white paper, the group has produced over 100 publications, which have gained wider acceptance in the industry and are being implemented in prominent open source projects like OpenStack, ONAP, Open Source MANO (OSM) to name a few.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Due to active cross-liaison activities, the ETSI NFV specifications are also being referenced in other SDOs like 3GPP, IETF, ETSI MEC etc.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Network functions virtualization infrastructure (NFVI) is the totality of all hardware and software components that build the environment where NFVs are deployed.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The NFV infrastructure can span several locations.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The network providing connectivity between these locations is considered as part of the NFV infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The building block for both the NFVI and the NFV-MANO is the NFV platform.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In the NFVI role, it consists of both virtual and physical processing and storage resources, and virtualization software.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In its NFV-MANO role it consists of VNF and NFVI managers and virtualization software operating on a hardware controller.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform implements carrier-grade features used to manage and monitor the platform components, recover from failures and provide effective security – all required for the public carrier network.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] A service provider that follows the NFV design implements one or more virtualized network functions, or *VNFs*.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] A VNF by itself does not automatically provide a usable product or service to the provider's customers.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] To build more complex services, the notion of *service chaining* is used, where multiple VNFs are used in sequence to deliver a service.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Another aspect of implementing NFV is the *orchestration* process.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] To build highly reliable and scalable services, NFV requires that the network be able to instantiate VNF instances, monitor them, repair them, and (most important for a service provider business) bill for the services rendered.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] These attributes, referred to as carrier-grade features, are allocated to an orchestration layer in order to provide high availability and security, and low operation and maintenance costs.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Importantly, the orchestration layer must be able to manage VNFs irrespective of the underlying technology within the VNF.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] For example, an orchestration layer must be able to manage an SBC VNF from vendor X running on VMware vSphere just as well as an IMS VNF from vendor Y running on KVM.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The initial perception of NFV was that virtualized capability should be implemented in data centers.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This approach works in many – but not all – cases.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] NFV presumes and emphasizes the widest possible flexibility as to the physical location of the virtualized functions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Ideally, therefore, virtualized functions should be located where they are the most effective and least expensive.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] That means a service provider should be free to locate NFV in all possible locations, from the data center to the network node to the customer premises.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This approach, known as distributed NFV, has been emphasized from the beginning as NFV was being developed and standardized, and is prominent in the recently released NFV ISG documents.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] For some cases there are clear advantages for a service provider to locate this virtualized functionality at the customer premises.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] These advantages range from economics to performance to the feasibility of the functions being virtualized.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The first ETSI NFV ISG-approved public multi-vendor proof of concept (PoC) of D-NFV was conducted by Cyan, Inc., RAD, Fortinet and Certes Networks in Chicago in June, 2014, and was sponsored by CenturyLink.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] It was based on RAD's dedicated customer-edge D-NFV equipment running Fortinet's Next Generation Firewall (NGFW) and Certes Networks’ virtual encryption/decryption engine as Virtual Network Functions (VNFs) with Cyan's Blue Planet system orchestrating the entire ecosystem.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] RAD's D-NFV solution, a Layer 2/Layer 3 network termination unit (NTU) equipped with a D-NFV X86 server module that functions as a virtualization engine at the customer edge, became commercially available by the end of that month.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] During 2014 RAD also had organized a D-NFV Alliance, an ecosystem of vendors and international systems integrators specializing in new NFV applications.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] When designing and developing the software that provides the VNFs, vendors may structure that software into software components (implementation view of a software architecture) and package those components into one or more images (deployment view of a software architecture).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] These vendor-defined software components are called VNF Components (VNFCs).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] VNFs are implemented with one or more VNFCs and it is assumed, without loss of generality, that VNFC instances map 1:1 to VM Images.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] VNFCs should in general be able to scale up and/or scale out.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] By being able to allocate flexible (virtual) CPUs to each of the VNFC instances, the network management layer can scale up (i.e., scale *vertically*) the VNFC to provide the throughput/performance and scalability expectations over a single system or a single platform.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, the network management layer can scale out (i.e., *scale horizontally*) a VNFC by activating multiple instances of such VNFC over multiple platforms and therefore reach out to the performance and architecture specifications whilst not compromising the other VNFC function stabilities.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Network Functions Virtualisation is highly complementary to SDN.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In essence, SDN is an approach to building data networking equipment and software that separates and abstracts elements of these systems.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] It does this by decoupling the control plane and data plane from each other, such that the control plane resides centrally and the forwarding components remain distributed.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The control plane interacts with both northbound and southbound.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In the northbound direction the control plane provides a common abstracted view of the network to higher-level applications and programs using high-level APIs and novel management paradigms, such as Intent-based networking.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] In the southbound direction the control plane programs the forwarding behavior of the data plane, using device level APIs of the physical network equipment distributed around the network.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts, but NFV and SDN can cooperate to enhance the management of a NFV infrastructure and to create a more dynamic network environment.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] An NFV system needs a central orchestration and management system that takes operator requests associated with an NS or a VNF, translates them into the appropriate processing, storage and network configuration needed to bring the NS or VNF into operation.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Once in operation, the VNF and the networks it is connected to potentially must be monitored for capacity and utilization, and adapted if necessary.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] All network control functions in an NFV infrastructure can be accomplished using SDN concepts and NFV could be considered one of the primary SDN use cases in service provider environments.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] For example, within each NFV infrastructure site, a VIM could rely upon an SDN controller to set up and configure the overlay networks interconnecting (e.g.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] VXLAN) the VNFs and PNFs composing an NS.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The SDN controller would then configure the NFV infrastructure switches and routers, as well as the network gateways, as needed.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, a Wide Area Infrastructure Manager (WIM) could rely upon an SDN controller to set up overlay networks to interconnect NSs that are deployed to different geo-located NFV infrastructures.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] It is also apparent that many SDN use-cases could incorporate concepts introduced in the NFV initiative.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Examples include where the centralized controller is controlling a distributed forwarding function that could in fact be also virtualized on existing processing or routing equipment.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] NFV has proven a popular standard even in its infancy.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Its immediate applications are numerous, such as virtualization of mobile base stations, platform as a service (PaaS), content delivery networks (CDN), fixed access and home environments.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The potential benefits of NFV is anticipated to be significant.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization of network functions deployed on general purpose standardized hardware is expected to reduce capital and operational expenditures, and service and product introduction times.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Many major network equipment vendors have announced support for NFV.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This has coincided with NFV announcements from major software suppliers who provide the NFV platforms used by equipment suppliers to build their NFV products.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] However, to realize the anticipated benefits of virtualization, network equipment vendors are improving IT virtualization technology to incorporate carrier-grade attributes required to achieve high availability, scalability, performance, and effective network management capabilities.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] To minimize the total cost of ownership (TCO), carrier-grade features must be implemented as efficiently as possible.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This requires that NFV solutions make efficient use of redundant resources to achieve five-nines availability (99.999%), and of computing resource without compromising performance predictability.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform is the foundation for achieving efficient carrier-grade NFV solutions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] It is a software platform running on standard multi-core hardware and built using open source software that incorporates carrier-grade features.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform software is responsible for dynamically reassigning VNFs due to failures and changes in traffic load, and therefore plays an important role in achieving high availability.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] There are numerous initiatives underway to specify, align and promote NFV carrier-grade capabilities such as ETSI NFV Proof of Concept, ATIS Open Platform for NFV Project, Carrier Network Virtualization Awards and various supplier ecosystems.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The vSwitch, a key component of NFV platforms, is responsible for providing connectivity both VM-to-VM (between VMs) and between VMs and the outside network.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Its performance determines both the bandwidth of the VNFs and the cost-efficiency of NFV solutions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The standard Open vSwitch's (OVS) performance has shortcomings that must be resolved to meet the needs of NFVI solutions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Significant performance improvements are being reported by NFV suppliers for both OVS and Accelerated Open vSwitch (AVS) versions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization is also changing the way availability is specified, measured and achieved in NFV solutions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] As VNFs replace traditional function-dedicated equipment, there is a shift from equipment-based availability to a service-based, end-to-end, layered approach.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Virtualizing network functions breaks the explicit coupling with specific equipment, therefore availability is defined by the availability of VNF services.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Because NFV technology can virtualize a wide range of network function types, each with their own service availability expectations, NFV platforms should support a wide range of fault tolerance options.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This flexibility enables CSPs to optimize their NFV solutions to meet any VNF availability requirement.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] ETSI has already indicated that an important part of controlling the NFV environment be done through automated orchestration.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] NFV Management and Orchestration (NFV-MANO) refers to a set of functions within an NFV system to manage and orchestrate the allocation of virtual infrastructure resources to virtualized network functions (VNFs) and network services (NSs).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] They are the brains of the NFV system and a key automation enabler.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The entry point in NFV-MANO for external operations support systems (OSS) and business support systems (BSS) is the NFVO, which is in charge of managing the lifecycle of NS instances.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The management of the lifecycle of VNF instances constituting an NS instance is delegated by the NFVO to one more or VNFMs.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Both the NFVO and the VNFMs uses the services exposed by one or more VIMs for allocating virtual infrastructure resources to the objects they manage.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Additional functions are used for managing containerized VNFs: the Container Infrastructure Service Management (CISM) and the Container Image Registry (CIR) functions.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The CISM is responsible for maintaining the containerized workloads while the CIR is responsible for storing and maintaining information of OS container software images The behavior of the NFVO and VNFM is driven by the contents of deployment templates (a.k.a.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] NFV descriptors) such as a Network Service Descriptor (NSD) and a VNF Descriptor (VNFD).
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] ETSI delivers a full set of standards **enabling an open ecosystem** where Virtualized Network Functions (VNFs) can be interoperable with independently developed management and orchestration systems, and where the components of a management and orchestration system are themselves interoperable.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] This includes a set of Restful API specifications as well as the specifications of a packaging format for delivering VNFs to service providers and of the deployment templates to be packaged with the software images to enable managing the lifecycle of VNFs.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Deployment templates can be based on TOSCA or YANG.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Swagger) representation of the API specifications is available and maintained on the ETSI forge server, along with TOSCA and YANG definition files to be used when creating deployment templates.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The full set of published specifications is summarized in the table below.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] An overview of the different versions of the OpenAPI representations of NFV-MANO APIs is available on the ETSI NFV wiki.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] The OpenAPI files as well as the TOSCA YAML definition files and YANG modules applicable to NFV descriptors are available on the ETSI Forge.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Recent performance study on NFV focused on the throughput, latency and jitter of virtualized network functions (VNFs), as well as NFV scalability in terms of the number of VNFs a single physical server can support.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] From 2018, many VNF providers began to migrate many of their VNFs to a container-based architecture.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Such VNFs also known as Cloud-Native Network Functions (CNF) utilize many innovations deployed commonly on internet infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] These include auto-scaling, supporting a continuous delivery / DevOps deployment model, and efficiency gains by sharing common services across platforms.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Through service discovery and orchestration, a network based on CNFs will be more resilient to infrastructure resource failures.
[src:open-ran/network-function-virtualization] Utilizing containers, and thus dispensing with the overhead inherent in traditional virtualization through the elimination of the guest OS can greatly increase infrastructure resource efficiency.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] For this reason, this technology assumes a central role to support 5G mobile networks that are designed to efficiently embrace a plethora of services with very different service level requirements (SLR).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The realization of this service-oriented view of the network leverages on the concepts of software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) that allow the implementation of flexible and scalable network slices on top of a common network infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] From a business model perspective, each network slice is administrated by a mobile virtual network operator (MVNO).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The infrastructure provider (the owner of the telecommunication infrastructure) leases its physical resources to the MVNOs that share the underlying physical network.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] According to the availability of the assigned resources, a MVNO can autonomously deploy multiple network slices that are customized to the various applications provided to its own users.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The history of network slicing can be tracked back to the late 1980s with the introduction of the concept of "slice" in the networking field.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Overlay networks provided the first form of network slicing since heterogeneous network resources were combined to create virtual networks over a common infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] However, they lacked a mechanism that could enable their programmability.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In the early 2000s, PlanetLab introduced a virtualization framework that allowed groups of users to program network functions in order to obtain isolated and application-specific slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The advent of SDN technologies in 2009 further extended the programmability capabilities via open interfaces that enabled the realization of fully configurable and scalable network slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In the context of mobile networks, network slicing evolved from the concept of RAN sharing that was initially introduced in the LTE standard.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Examples of such technology are multi-operator radio access networks (MORAN) and multi-operator core networks (MOCN), which allow network operators to share common LTE resources within the same radio access network (RAN).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Network slicing emerges as an essential technique in 5G networks to accommodate such different and possibly contrasting quality of service (QoS) requirements exploiting a single physical network infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The basic idea of network slicing is to "slice" the original network architecture in multiple logical and independent networks that are configured to effectively meet the various services requirements.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In commercial terms, network slicing allows a mobile operator to create specific virtual networks that cater to particular clients and use cases.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Certain applications - such as mobile broadband, machine-to-machine communications (e.g. in manufacturing or logistics), or smart cars - will benefit from leveraging different aspects of 5G technology.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] One might require higher speeds, another low latency, and yet another access to edge computing resources.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] By creating separate slices that prioritise specific resources a 5G operator can offer tailored solutions to particular industries.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Some sources insist this will revolutionise industries like marketing, augmented reality, or mobile gaming, while others are more cautious, pointing to unevenness in network coverage and poor reach of advantages beyond increased speed.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Slicing will be very useful to MVNOs as different use cases can be supported in a layer based on parameters like low latency high speed for video streaming for OTT focused MVNOs, similarly telemetry operations could have lower speed parameter and as on.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Although there are different proposals of network slice architectures, it is possible to define a general architecture that maps the common elements of each solution into a general and unified framework.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] From a high-level perspective, the network slicing architecture can be considered as composed of two mains blocks, one dedicated to the actual slice implementation and the other dedicated to the slice management and configuration.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The first block is designed as a multi-tier architecture composed by three layers (service layer, network function layer, infrastructure layer), where each one contributes to the slice definition and deployment with distinct tasks.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The second block is designed as a centralized network entity, generically denoted as *network slice controller*, that monitors and manages the functionalities between the three layers in order to efficiently coordinate the coexistence of multiple slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The service layer interfaces directly with the network business entities (e.g.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] MVNOs and 3rd party service providers) that share the underlying physical network and it provides a unified vision of the service requirements.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Each service is formally represented as *service instance*, which embeds all the network characteristics in the form of SLA requirements that are expected to be fully satisfied by a suitable slice creation.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The network function layer is in charge of the creation of each network slice according to service instance requests coming from the upper layer.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] It is composed of a set of *network functions* that embody well-defined behaviors and interfaces.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Multiple network functions are placed over the virtual network infrastructure and chained together to create an end-to-end network slice instance that reflects the network characteristics requested by the service.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The configuration of the network functions are performed by means of a set of *network operations* that allow management of their full lifecycle (from their placement when a slice is created to their de-allocation when the function provided is no longer needed).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] To increase resource usage efficiency, the same network function can be simultaneously shared by different slices at the cost of an increase in the complexity of operations management.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Conversely, a one-to-one mapping between each network function and each slice eases the configuration procedures, but can lead to poor and inefficient resource usage.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The infrastructure layer represents the actual physical network topology (radio access network, transport network and core network) upon which every network slice is multiplexed and it provides the physical network resources to host the several network functions composing each slice.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The network domain of the available resources includes a heterogeneous set of infrastructure components like data centers (storage and computation capacity resources), devices enabling network connectivity such as routers (networking resources) and base stations (radio bandwidth resources).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The network slice controller is defined as a network orchestrator, which interfaces with the various functionalities performed by each layer to coherently manage each slice request.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The benefit of such network element is that it enables an efficient and flexible slice creation that can be reconfigured during its life-cycle.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Due to the complexity of the performed tasks which address different purposes, the network slice controller can be composed by multiple orchestrators that independently manage a subset of functionalities of each layer.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] To fulfill the service requirements, the various orchestration entities need to coordinate with each other by exchanging high-level information about the state of the operations involved in the slice creation and deployment.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Slice isolation is an important requirement that allows enforcing the core concept of network slicing about the simultaneous coexistence of multiple slices sharing the same infrastructure.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] This property is achieved by imposing that each slice's performance must not have any impact on the other slice's performance.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Slicing has become an important part of 5G networks, but it doesn't have to forget to guarantee the QoS.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Some studies have demonstrated that formulating the problem with the QoS as a stochastic problem, permit us to maximize the average throughput of the AP, while satisfying the constraints related to the QoS.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Monetizing 5G services faster is one of the topics that interests network operators the most because the costs of building and maintaining 5G networks are high, and it's difficult to predict the demand for 5G services.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] 5G network slicing is one of the effective ways to offer customized services for different industries such as manufacturing, transportation, and healthcare.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Combined with AIOps, ML/AI-driven automation and 5G lifecycle optimization, it can reduce OpEx and increase revenues for network operators.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In the 3GPP 5G core architecture, the user plane and control plane functions are separated.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Control plane capabilities, for instance, session management, access authentication, policy management, and user data storage are independent of the user plane functionality.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The user plane handles packet forwarding, encapsulation or de-capsulation, and associated transport level specifics.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] This separation leads to the distribution of the user plane functions close to the edge of network slices (e.g., so as to reduce latency) and to be independent of the control plane.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The AMF (as a function of the CP) controls UEs that have been authenticated to use the services of the operator and manages the mobility of the UEs across the gNBs.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The SMF (again part of the CP) manages the sessions of UEs, while AMF transmits the session management messages between the UEs and SMF.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] UPF (as part of the UP) performs the processing and forwarding of the user data.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] NSSF (as a function of the CP) is responsible for the management and orchestration of network slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] CSMF (as a function of the CP) translates the requirements of services to requirements relating to network slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] 5G Core network functions can be sliced to support specific services for different UEs.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Thanks to the modular nature of the 5G core, the network functions of the 5G core can be split and shared between different network slices to reduce management complexity.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In general, we can perform 5G core network slicing in two ways.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] We can implement dedicated core network functions per network slice.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] In this architecture, each network slice has a set of completely dedicated core network functions (e.g., AUSF, AMF, SMF, and UDM).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The UEs can access various services from network slices and different core networks.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Alternatively, we can share some control plane functions between the network slices while others such as user plane functions are slice specific (e.g., UPF).
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] AMF is usually shared by several network slices, while SMF and UPF are usually dedicated to specific network slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The AMF function will be shared between different network slices in order to reduce the mobility management signaling when the UE uses the services of different network slices simultaneously.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] For example, UE location management or the control signaling between the UE and the old AMF will be reduced when it will be connected to the new AMF of another network slice.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Also, UDM and NSSF are typically shared by all network slices to reduce the management complexity of network slices.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] The emergence of network slicing also exposes novel security and privacy challenges, primarily related to aspects such as network slicing life-cycle security, inter-slice security, intra-slice security, slice broker security, zero-touch network and management security, and blockchain security.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Therefore, enhancing the security, privacy, and trust of network slicing has become a key research area toward realizing the true capabilities of 5G.
[src:open-ran/network-slicing] Various security solutions are proposed for resolving the security threats, challenges, and issues of network slicing.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] Those open interfaces aim for mixing components from different vendors and quicker deployment of new services.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] Open RAN standardization is led by the O-RAN ALLIANCE.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] In Open RAN, the RAN is split into three main blocks: the Radio Unit (RU), the Distributed Unit (DU), and the Centralised Unit (CU).
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The RU performs basic RF and low-PHY functions such as precoding and beamforming.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The DU performs additional PHY functions such as scrambling and modulation, and handles MAC and RLC functions such as radio resource allocation.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The CU handles functions such as SDAP and RRC.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The near-RT RIC houses *xApps*, which are programs that optimize functions such as beamforming, traffic steering, and power control.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The non-RT RIC houses *rApps*, which manage longer-term policies such as network slicing.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The fronthaul interface lies between radio Units (RU) and baseband units (Distributed Units (DU)).
[src:open-ran/open-ran] O-RAN has specified an eCPRI-based 7.2x open interface to be used in the fronthaul, allowing connections between radio units and baseband units of different vendors.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] The near-RT RIC really houses multiple interworking components.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] O-RAN ALLIANCE (O-RAN) was founded in 2018 by AT&T, China Mobile, Deutsche Telekom, NTT DOCOMO and Orange to promote open mobile networks.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] O-RAN has over 30 operator members and almost 300 contributors.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] O-RAN specifications define the parts of the O-RAN Architecture, which can be used to develop Open RAN solutions.
[src:open-ran/open-ran] O-RAN ALLIANCE also handles the activities of the earlier xRAN and C-RAN forums.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
