[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:open-ran/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
